AFRICAN SWINE FEVER - MADAGASCAR (03)
*************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
See Also
African swine fever - Madagascar 990116130452
African swine fever - Madagascar (02) 990118215239
African plague, pigs - Madagascar 990108135337
Date: 11 Jan, 1999
Source: OIE Reports

Emergency report
Translation of a fax received on 11 January 1999 from Dr Andriambololona
Ratovo, Director of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Animal Production,
Antananarivo:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory, following suspicion.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: June 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
Toliary province 6
Antananarivo province 6
Mahajanga province 4

Description of affected population: the morbidity rate is 50 to 70%, in all
age categories and systems (extensive, semi-intensive, intensive).
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
susceptible: 510,765
cases: 153,229
deaths: 107,260
destroyed: 57*
slaughtered: 350
* buried
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: CNEVA, Maisons-Alfort, France (17
December 1998).
B. Diagnostic tests used:
- ELISA(1) serum antibody test: positive for both classical and African
swine fever (ASF);
- PCR(2): negative for classical swine fever, positive for ASF;
- the sequencing of a PCR-amplified segment (ASF primer) confirmed the
presence of an ASF virus.Epidemiology: an assessement of the risk factors
is being carried out with assistance of the FAO EMPRES(3) programme.
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: the source of infection is being
investigated since no live swine have ever been imported into Madagascar.
B. Mode of spread: through nation-wide trade movements of live swine,
cooked or uncooked pig meat, and due to the use of manure.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine and movement control
inside the country;
testing; voluntary stamping-out (as it is not possible to compensate the
owners for the time being); control of arthropods.
(1) ELISA: enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay.
(2) PCR: polymerase chain reaction.
(3) EMPRES: Emergency Prevention System
--
